>>>> This would be my second postdoc position, so I really need to be thinking about developing my own research identity. So, firstly, regarding the project I wonder how much flexibility there might be to continue to develop my own research interests (which are clearly related to the Dams project), and how much time would be spent on project deliverables which in isolation may have limited scientific novelty?
>>>> 
>>> 
>>> There will be lots of scope to do your own thing in relation to the project. As I mentioned briefly in the interview this project and the position are related to two other projects, one on water/food security in sub-Saharan Africa (BRECcIA) and one on agricultural monitoring/forecasting in drylands (AgSim). Although they are officially separate projects I see that they can leverage from each other and so the individual postdocs can contribute to broader questions on water/food and global change. As you note, there are a few things that we have to do for the project, i.e. provide streamflow predictions to drive an integrated water-energy-food-economy model for historic and future scenarios, which may have some intrinsic research value, but outside of that there is lots of flexibility to work on water related questions, not just in the case study regions but in a broader context so as to have more research impact.
>>> 
>>>> Similarly, one of the key things I'm looking for is a research group where I can play an active role in attracting research funding and, in consequence, extending the initial two year position. Specifically, I plan in the next few years to prepare a fellowship application (e.g. NERC, Royal Society). All else being equal, is this something you could support?
>>>> 
>>> 
>>> Yes certainly. The expectation is that postdocs do the research but also have full opportunities to develop their career potential and be set up for their next job/project. So I’m very happy to support this. 
>>> 
>>>> One of the main potential attractions of the job is to learn and develop from others, including yourself, by working collaboratively. Is this a realistic expectation?
>>> 
>>> Yes. Physically you will sit in the Geography department where we now have 4 other postdocs working on the above projects with two more expected to start in the next few months, on disciplines such as water resources, hydrological forecasting, remote sensing, community resilience, capacity development, … - there will be lots of opportunities to work together and learn from each other. 
>>> 
>>> I generally meet with postdocs/students once a week on average, to ensure that there is regular interaction and that they get good feedback. 
>>> 
>>> There is also the broader set of phds that I supervise/co-supervise who are working on droughts, natural flood management, and community resilience to climate variability, and a new PhD starting this week working on drought impacts on water/food in South Pacific islands. There are also a range of postodcs/phds within Geography who are working on various aspects of global challenges (e.g. climate adaptation, natural resources management, sustainable development, …) all of whom you will interact with via various informal/formal activities. In particular, you will be a member of a broader research group (Environmental Change and Sustainability) that I lead, which includes about 12 academic staff and their associated postdocs and PhDs. The research group organizes informal gatherings to share ideas, a monthly seminar series, training opportunities, a research away day in the early summer and various social activities. 
>>> 
